class="col_A"><h1><a
href="/">Get Insider Tips For Healthy Living On A Budget</a></h1><p><img
class="size-thumbnail wp-image-43185 alignleft" title="cut-day12-main" src="http://www.learnvest.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/cut-day12-main-190x130.jpg" alt="" width="190" height="130" /> Food is one of our biggest expenses and averages 15% of <a
href="http://www.learnvest.com/mylv/pages/toolsAndCalculators/budget">household budgets</a>.  Everyone knows it&#8217;s more cost effective to eat at home than to dine out, but trips to the grocery store can also add up.  Here are some tips to make the most of your food budget:</p><h3>Start With A Strategy.</h3><p>Nothing is more persuasive than your stomach, so make sure it&#8217;s satisfied before you breach those sliding doors. Our favorite tactic is <a
href="http://www.learnvest.com/living-frugally/food_and_drink/the-easiest-way-to-save-money-at-the-grocery-store/">perimeter shopping</a>—sticking to the aisles of the store along the perimeter—since the most expensive and least healthy foods are toward the middle.</p><h3>Make The Most Of The Leftovers.</h3><p>Don&#8217;t be afraid to <a
href="http://www.learnvest.com/living-frugally/food_and_drink/how-to-stretch-your-leftovers-and-whip-up-quick-easy-meals/">repurpose leftovers</a> by adding in additional ingredients like onions, carrots, cheese, and eggs. Prep the new ingredients first, as the leftovers should be the last thing you add to the concoction since they require heat, not more cooking.</p><p
style="text-align: center;"><img
class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-43574" style="border-top: 1px dashed #D1D3D4; margin-top: 10px; padding-top: 20px;" title="text" src="http://www.learnvest.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/text.png" alt="" width="381" height="58" /></p></div><div
